# OTel Java mechanics

- Obtain tracers via `TelemetryProvider.getTracer(INSTRUMENTATION_NAME)`. Never call `GlobalOpenTelemetry.get()` in library code.
- Open every `Scope` in try-with-resources. End every `Span` in `finally`. A leaked Scope corrupts context for the whole thread.
- When submitting work to an Executor, ExecutorService, or CompletableFuture, wrap the task: `Context.current().wrap(task)`. Neither trace context nor Baggage crosses thread pools automatically.
- Attribute keys come from `NorthgateAttributes` or the current `opentelemetry-semconv` classes. Never write inline attribute-key string literals. When unsure whether a semconv key or API is current, check @Docs (OTel Java SDK, OTel semantic conventions) — the upstream spec deprecates and renames; do not rely on memorized names.
- Span names are low-cardinality route templates (`GET /orders/{id}`). High-cardinality values (IDs, URLs) go in attributes, never names.
- New processors/exporters wire through the central BatchSpanProcessor configuration in TelemetryProvider. SimpleSpanProcessor is forbidden outside tests. Vendor-specific attribute mapping belongs at the Collector, not in application code.
- Catch blocks on instrumented paths call `span.recordException(e)` and `span.setStatus(StatusCode.ERROR)` before rethrowing or handling.
- When scaffolding instrumentation, also scaffold a JUnit 5 test using `InMemorySpanExporter` (see /telemetry-test for the pattern).
